         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">2/5/89 ¶  ¶ This evening, dear Prof. Balfour, I received your magnificent vol. on the vegetation of Socotra. ¶  What a marvelous complex of plants there and remaining unknown til near the end of the 1...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">89.05.02</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Bayley Balfour</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Royal Botanic Gardens Edinburgh, I. B. Balfour Correspondence</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">2/5/89</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This evening, dear Prof. Balfour, I received your magnificent vol. on the vegetation of Socotra.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I. Balfour (1888).</p>
               </note> What a marvelous complex of plants there and remaining unknown til near the end of the 19th century, altho' that island was within the course of navigation and commerce since antiquity. How singularly remarkable also, that such genera as Begonia reach comparatively so near the Mediterranean Sea! Much am I also interested in your <name key="Acacia%20Socotrana">Acacia Socotrana</name>, because it strengthens the view of Prof Fraas, that A. Farnesiana is the ακακια of Kappadocia of Dioscorides, as that plant cannot possibly be the <name key="Cytisus%20scoparius">Cytisus scoparius</name>, though assumed so by Sprengel.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>C. Fraas (1845), pp. 65-6; Sprengel (1807-8), vol. 1, p. 97. See also M to G. Bentham, 12 February 1877, and G. Bentham to M, 30 April 1877. </p>
               </note> When I explored with Gregory very far inland in N.W. Australia during 1855 and 1856 I found the true <name key="Acacia%20Farnesiana">Acacia Farnesiana</name> abundantly as a wild plant, the nearest eastern settlement then being 3000 miles off and the nearest S. Western 2000 miles! The ακακια of Egypt of Disoscorides is clearly A. vera, i.e., A. Arabica, which is also Plinius' &amp; Vergilius' Acacia. I cannot see, how A. Farnesiana can be indigenous to America solely in the present sense of nativity, when it was so common in Central Australia long before even its geographic exploration. The cases of <name key="Cocos">Cocos</name>, Cucurbita, <name key="Phaseolus">Phaseolus</name> &amp;c are not analogous.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As this splendid work of yours is published by the R.S. Ed., I am reminded, that the Edinb. Soc. received hardly any publications from me for years. But for a long while the Gov. publications here all are distributed <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">only</hi>
               </seg> through the Public Library of Melbourne on order of the Premier. If the Soc. should like, to possess any of my works, it would be best to apply <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">directly</hi>
               </seg> to the Librarian here, Dr Bride, to whom some of the later volumes of your transactions might be sent in return.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>"Entre nous" I might say, that I purchased each of the last 3 years over £50— of my own works on my private expense from the Gov Printing Office for giving away.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This paragraph is written in the margin of p. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>4. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You might successfully search for <name key="Chenolea%20hirsuta">Chenolea hirsuta</name> at the Scottish Coast. I found it nearly as far north in Schleswig, and in Sweden it extends also to Oeland.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Öland, second largest Swedish island.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> It is in is almost glabrous state easily taken for <name key="Suaeda%20maritima">Suaeda maritima</name>.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This paragraph is written in the margins of p. 1. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The duties of the Presidency of the Austral. Assoc for the Advancm. of Science commence to press heavily on me. The meeting takes place [Jan] 1890. We hope to arrange a tour to the glaciers of the Austral Alps.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This paragraph is written in the margin of p. 2.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I triangulated <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">first</hi>
               </seg> through a large portion of the Victorian Alps 1853, 1854 &amp; 1855.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This paragraph is written in the margin of p. 3. See Home (2014).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
